solutions.content:
> **Divide into subproblems**
The root candidate can be selected from `[1, N]`.

> **Recursively solve subproblems**
After we decide a root `x`, two subtrees (i.e. subproblems) generated. One contains nodes with values with the range `[1, x - 1]`, while the other contains nodes with values within the range `[x + 1, N]`. 
We can solve subproblems separately following the pattern described above.
Until there is no nodes left to set as root (detected by `start > end`), we terminate the recursion after we add `null` to the current placement.

>**Conquer results of subproblems**
Combine the results of subproblems, i.e. try all possible combinations of a node's left child and right child to construct subtrees from bottom to top. 


**More on Recursion**
The return type of `generateTreesFrom()` is `List<TreeNode>`, which indicates all roots of generated trees until now. We receive the results(`i.e. leftSub, rightSub`), construct trees by all combinations of them, and add roots to the newly created result list of the current stack frame. The pseudo-code is as below:
```
            init curret result;
            for  leftNode in leftSub {
                for rightNode in rightSub {
                    create root node with value x;
                    attach leftNode, rightNode to root 
                    add root to curret result; 
                }
            }
			return curret result;
```
