**Intution** : For understanding the intution of this problem lets take some sorted sample inputs.

**Input 1 when size of array is odd** : [1,2,3,4,5]
What is the median? if we consider this as simple mathmatical problem median element will be n/2 element. So it will be 3.

let say we divied this array in 2 parts
																1,2,3  ||||||   4,5
so in case when n is odd our median element is first element on the left of divider(i.e. ||||||).

now lets say we want to add element 0 in above arrangement. where this 0 element should go,
is it on the left of divider or on the right, in such a way sorting order is maintained?

0 is less then 3 so it should go on the left of divider. 

so arrangement will become 
												0,1,2,3  ||||||   4,5

what will be the median now?
since n now become even if we consider this as simple mathematical probelm then median will become average of 2 middle element, so median is (2+3)/2 = 1.5 

let say we now want to add 7. where this element should be placed ? it should be on the right of divider.

0,1,2,3  ||||||   4,5,7

what will be the median? it will 3. (7/2th element).

Now if we keep getting elements that are less then 3 then left size will keep growing. so we need to balance number of element on each side of divider( that is element should jump from left to right or right to left but we should make a contract that element can jump only from left to right or from right to left).

Let say we made a contract the size different between left-right<=1. That mean either both sides of the divider are equal or  left can have atmost 1 element greater then right. If due to addition of some element we are breaking this balancing then we need rebalance( or move element from left to right) in order to balance the of divider.

lets consider this arrangement.

0,1  ||||||   4

**what is the median ? it is 1st element from left of divider (n=3, n/2= 1) so answer is 1. and this element is the maximum element from all elements on the left hand side? So that mean we are only intreseted in the max of left. Can't we max it max heap then?
**

let say we want to add -1 in above arrangement.

-1 will go on the left as it less then 1 but if we do this left part will have 2 more element the right.
then simple solution is move 1 from left to right and then add -1 so arrangement will become.

-1.0 ||||| 1,4

what is the median?  it will  be avarage of middle elements (0+1)/2 = 0.5 if you observer 0 is max element of left and 1 is min element of right. so we are only intersted in min and max elemenet.
lets represet left part with max heap then and right part with min heap.

when n is even or sizeof(minheap) == sizeof(maxheap) in this case just peek max of left and peek min of right and divide it by 2.


Now you just need to figure out do you need to move element from left to right or where to add element. Trying tracing some sample input. Figure it out. And if you still need any help feel free to debug and go through the code.










```
class MedianFinder {

    private PriorityQueue<Integer> maxHeap, minHeap;
    public MedianFinder() {
         maxHeap = new PriorityQueue<>(Comparator.reverseOrder());
         minHeap = new PriorityQueue<>();
    }

    public void addNum(int num) {
        if(maxHeap.size()==0)
            maxHeap.add(num);
        else if(maxHeap.size()>minHeap.size()) {
            if(num>maxHeap.peek()) {
                minHeap.add(num);
            }else {
                int temp = maxHeap.remove();
                minHeap.add(temp);
                maxHeap.add(num);
            }
        }else {
            if(num<maxHeap.peek() || num<minHeap.peek()) {
                maxHeap.add(num);
            }
            else {
                int temp = minHeap.remove();
                minHeap.add(num);
                maxHeap.add(temp);

            }
        }
    }

    public double findMedian() {
        if(maxHeap==null || maxHeap.size()==0)
            return -1d;
        if(maxHeap.size()==minHeap.size()) {
            return (maxHeap.peek()+minHeap.peek())*1.0/2;
        }else{
            return (double)maxHeap.peek();
        }
    }
}

/**
 * Your MedianFinder object will be instantiated and called as such:
 * MedianFinder obj = new MedianFinder();
 * obj.addNum(num);
 * double param_2 = obj.findMedian();
 */
```
