solutions.content:
The base idea here is to keep constanly the data received into 2 halves and keep rebalancing them as we go inserting more.

To do so, we will create 2 heaps:
* `lows` is a maxheap that will collect the lower half of the values;
* `highs`, specularly, is a minhap that will collect the upper half.

We will do nothing in the constructor and move on with the `addNum` method, in which we will take the provided input `val` and:
* push `val` into `lows` if `lows` had no previous elements or `val < lows.top()`;
* push `val` into `highs` otherwise;
* rebalance the heaps to make sure that `lows` is never smaller and their difference in size is never `> 1`, moving the currently top element from one to the other.

In the `findMedian` method we can go and, if the number of provided elements so far is odd (ie: `lows.size() > highs.size()`) we will just return `lows.tops()`, otherwise we will return the average of both `.top()`s, since they are the central values :)

The code:

```cpp
class MedianFinder {
    priority_queue<int> lows;
    priority_queue<int, vector<int>, greater<int>> highs;
public:
    /** initialize your data structure here. */
    MedianFinder() {}

    void addNum(int val) {
        // deciding in which half val goes:
        if (lows.empty() || val < lows.top()) lows.push(val);
        else highs.push(val);
        // rebalancing to avoid higher becoming bigger
        if (lows.size() < highs.size()) {
            lows.push(highs.top());
            highs.pop();
        }
        // or lows growing more than 1 element from the size of highs
        else if (lows.size() > highs.size() + 1) {
            highs.push(lows.top());
            lows.pop();
        }
    }

    double findMedian() {
        // computing the result depengn if we have seen odd amount of elements or not
        return lows.size() > highs.size() ? lows.top() : (lows.top() + highs.top()) / 2.0;
    }
};
```

