# Intuition
basically we want to mantain 2 heaps.
maxheap will apparently have all the elements to the left of the media. minheap will apparently have all the elements to the right of the median

The main property of the median is that all elements before the median are smaller than itself and all elements after the median are larger than itself, thus we assume 2 arrays (heaps actually).

# Complexity
- Time complexity for addNum: $$O(logn)$$ 
- Time complexity for findMedian: $$O(1)$$ 

- Space complexity: $$O(n)$$


# Code
```
class MedianFinder {
public:
  priority_queue<int, vector<int>, greater<int>> minHeap;
  priority_queue<int> maxHeap;
    MedianFinder() {

    }
    //basically we want to mantain 2 heaps.
    // maxheap will apparently have all the elements to the left of the median 
    //minheap will apparently have all the elements to the right of the median
    void addNum(int num) {

        //we'll check if the element should go to the left side of the array (before median) 
        //or to the right side of the array (after median)
        if (maxHeap.empty() || maxHeap.top()>num) maxHeap.push(num); 
        else minHeap.push(num);


        //but after inserting there is a possibility that we disrupted the balance between the heaps.
        // we need both heaps to have equal size or differ at max by 1.
        if (maxHeap.size()>minHeap.size()+1){
            minHeap.push(maxHeap.top());
            maxHeap.pop();
            //removed topmost element from maxHeap and pushed it to minHeap.
        } 
        else if (minHeap.size()>maxHeap.size()+1){
            maxHeap.push(minHeap.top());
            minHeap.pop();
            //removed topmost element from minHeap and pushed it to maxHeap.
        } 


    }

    double findMedian() {

        if (maxHeap.size()==minHeap.size()){
            if (maxHeap.empty()) return 0; //the first case where we did not input any number and directly asked for a median.
            else return (double) (maxHeap.top()+minHeap.top())/2.0;
            // because median is the average of 2 middles when length is even
        }
        else{
            // if the size is not equal then return the top of the largest heap simply
            if (maxHeap.size()>minHeap.size()) return maxHeap.top();
            else return minHeap.top();
        }

    }
};

