solutions.content:
### Concept
* Lets take two priority queues, imagining that they are the left half and right half of the array of integers. 
* The median is the one that is calculated from the center elements.
* Therefore we want the maximum integer from the left side and minimum integer from the right side. This concludes that the left pq will be a max heap and the right pq will be a min min heap.

### Addition of Elements
* We allways add a new element in the left pq, and later check if the count of elements have become even then we will remove the maximum element from the left pq and add it to the right pq, to equally distribute the elements. Also pq automantically adjusts the maximum and minimum elements so we do not have to worry.
* Whenever we adda new element to the left side, firstly we check for the size (in prev point), else we will check if the max of left is greater than the min of right, then we will swap them, or else if will later create conflicts. Since we always want to have lower elements in the left and higher ones in the right.

### Find Median
* Check if size of left pq is greater than the size of right pq, then return the peek of left. Since this will be the median. [case of odd numbers].
* Else we take peeks of both pqs and return the median. [case of even numbers]

```
class MedianFinder {

    /** initialize your data structure here. */

    PriorityQueue<Integer> left;
    PriorityQueue<Integer> right;

    int l, r;

    public MedianFinder() {
        left=new PriorityQueue<>(Collections.reverseOrder());
        right=new PriorityQueue<>();

        l=0;
        r=0;
    }

    public void addNum(int num) {
        left.add(num);
        l++;

        if (l-r>1) {
            right.add(left.poll());
            l--;
            r++;
        } else if (right.size()>0 && left.peek()>right.peek()) {
            int temp1=left.poll();
            int temp2=right.poll();

            left.add(temp2);
            right.add(temp1);

        }

    }

    public double findMedian() {

        if (l>r) {
            return left.peek();
        } else {
            return (left.peek()+right.peek())/2.0;
        }
    }
}
```

