# Approach
1. Create an **unordered_map** ***freq*** to count the freq of each character in the string ***s***.
2. Find the first character with frequency less than k using a while loop that iterates through ***s***.
3. If all char have valid freq -> return **s.length()**;
4. Otherwise, split the substring in 2 parts : **left part** from beginning of string to the first invalid char & **right part** from the first invalid char to the end of the string.
5. Recursively call **longestSubstring** function on both parts to find the longest valid substring.
6. The length of the longest valid susbtring is the **max** value of the lengths of left & right substrings.
7. Return the max length of substrings found.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: ***O(nlogn)***

![leetcode_395.jpg](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/453641d0-622f-41e1-9cee-e88719ede7f5_1678856314.9428208.jpeg)

_Please upvote if you found it useful!_

_Follow my **[Github](https://github.com/HimeshKohad)** for more such solutions and DSA content._ 


# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int longestSubstring(string s, int k) {
        int n = s.length();
        unordered_map <char, int> freq;

        //count the frequency of each char in the string 's'
        for (char c : s) {
            freq[c]++;
        }

        // find the first char with freq < k
        int i = 0;
        while (i < n && freq[s[i]] >= k) {
            i++;
        }

        // base case - whole string has valid frequencies
        if (i == n) return n;

        // recursively search for valid substrings in between invalid characters
        int left = longestSubstring(s.substr(0, i), k);

        while (i < n && freq[s[i]] < k) {
            i++;
        }

        int right = (i < n) ? longestSubstring(s.substr(i), k) : 0;

        return max(left, right);
    }
};
```

