solutions.content:
This is how it works : 
1. Loop through the string , store the counts into an array
2. Loop through the string again , but this time treat the characters that have `count < k` as break points , that break string into multiple segments ( this is the divide part )
3. Now each of this segment has the same problem again, so keep on recursivley dividing until there is no chance for anymore partitioning .. then you get the maximum substring length from one of those strings ( this is the conquering part )

```
class Solution {
    public int longestSubstring(String s, int k) {
        int n = s.length();
        if(n < k)return 0;

        int[] mem = new int[26];
        int count = 0; // this will be used to determine whether the whole string works out

        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            char ch = s.charAt(i);
            int t = ++mem[ch - 'a'];
            if(t == 1) // a new character ? increment the count
                count++;
            if(t == k) // some character is worth ? decrement the count
                count--;
        }

        if(count == 0)return n; // if every character cancelled out itself, means the whole string is acceptable

        int max = 0;
        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder(); // holder for substrings

        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            char ch = s.charAt(i);
            if(mem[ch - 'a'] < k){ // found a break point
                max = Math.max( max, longestSubstring(sb.toString(),k) ); // now solve this sub-problem
                sb = new StringBuilder(); // get ready for next substring after  the break point
            }
            else
                sb.append(ch); // build the string until a breakpoint 
        }
        max = Math.max(max,longestSubstring(sb.toString(),k)); // one last check for last sub string

        return max;
    }
}
```

